definition.value: Any compound which induces a partially or terminally differentiated cell to revert to an earlier developmental stage.
An antagonist at the A3 receptor.
An enzyme inhibitor that inhibits the action of any of the topoisomerases (enzymes that regulate the overwinding or underwinding of DNA).
Any substance that inhibits the polymerisation of the protein actin.
Any protein kinase inhibitor that inhibits the action of an Aurora kinase (a group of serine/threonine kinases that are essential for cell proliferation).
Any substance which blocks the painful sensation of heat caused by capsaicin acting on the TRPV1 ion channel.
Any compound which acts on the peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor.
A PPAR modulator which activates the peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor-alpha.
An enzyme inhibitor that interferes with the action of glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate dehydrogenase (EC 1.2.1.12)
A cysteine protease inhibitor which inhibits cathepsin L (EC 3.4.22.15).
A cysteine protease inhibitor which inhibits papain (EC 3.4.22.2).
An antiprotozoal drug used to treat or prevent infections caused by protozoan parasites that belong to the genus Leishmania.
Any entity used to generate reactive oxygen species.
An agonist that binds to and activates G-protein-coupled receptors
An antagonist at the AMPA receptor.
A hormone receptor modulator that acts as a complete or partial agonist or as an antagonist at the progesterone receptor.
Any drug that has been developed specifically for treatment of a rare medical condition, the condition itself being known as an orphan disease.
An effector that binds and activates the enzyme carbamylphosphate synthetase I

A compound that blocks the processing of the Gag precursor protein in HIV-1 by the viral protease enzyme, leading to the formation of noninfectious, immature virus particles that are incapable of infecting other cells.
A histamine agonist that binds to and activates H1-receptors.
An enzyme inhibitor that interferes with the action of N-acetylserotonin methyltransferase (EC 2.1.1.4)
An enzyme inhibitor that interferes with the action of Sir2.
An agonist that binds to and activates glucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1) receptors.
Any intra-glandular substance that acts as a precursor of a hormone, usually having minimal hormonal effect itself. Prohormones generally help in amplifying the effect of existing hormones.
An antagonist at any adenosine receptor.

A signalling molecule produced and used by bacteria participating in quorum sensing, that is, in cell-cell communication to coordinate community-wide regulation of processes such as biofilm formation, virulence, and bioluminescence in populations of bacteria. Such communication can occur both within and between different species of bacteria.
An enzyme inhibitor that inhibits the enzyme fatty acid synthase (EC 2.3.1.85), a multi-enzyme protein involved in fatty acid synthesis.
An enzyme inhibitor that interferes with the action of acid ceramidase.
A PPAR modulator which activates the peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor-gamma.
An insecticide that acts as a repellent to insects.
A phosphodiesterase inhibitor that specifically blocks the action of phosphodiesterase V (EC 3.1.4.17).
An enzyme inhibitor that interferes with the action of peptide deformylase (EC 3.5.1.88) involved in the catalytic removal of N-terminal formyl group of nascent proteins.
Any molecule shown to have the potentiality in stimulating the effect of nerve growth factor.
An inhibitor that interferes with the action of MTP.
An agonist that binds to and activates glucagon-like peptide-2 (GLP-2) receptors.

Any toxin secreted by bacteria, viruses, fungi or protozoa enabling them to achieve colonisation of a niche in the host, inhibit or evade the host's immune response, enter and exit cells, or obtain nutrition from the host.
A provitamin that can be converted into vitamin B1 by enzymes from animal tissues.
An inhibitor that interferes with vesicular glutamate transport.
Any compound that promotes the growth of new blood vessels from pre-existing vessels.
unclear how this differs from angiogenesis inducing agent -- cjm
A pheromone which is released by an organism when damaged by a predator which warns other individuals that there is a danger.
An enzyme inhibitor that interferes with the action of transglutaminase-2 (EC 2.3.2.13).
An agonist that binds to and activates aryl hydrocarbon receptors (AhRs).
Any inhibitor of breast cancer resistance protein (ABCG2).
Any inhibitor of the biosynthesis of carotenoids.

Any compound that inhibits the action of phytoene dehydrogenase (phytoene desaturase), an enzyme of carotenoid biosynthesis that converts phytoene into zeta-carotene (zeta-carotene) via the symmetrical introduction of two double bonds at the C-11 and C-11' positions of phytoene.
An enzyme inhibitor that interferes with the action of indoleamine 2,3-dioxygenase (EC 1.13.11.52).
An enzyme inhibitor that inhibits the action of EC 1.1.1.184, carbonyl reductase (NADPH).
An inhibitor of peroxidases (EC 1.11.1.*) that inhibits the action of L-ascorbate peroxidase, EC 1.11.1.11.
Any compound that protects plants by activating their defence mechanisms.
Any compound that inhibits one or more steps in the pathway leading to the synthesis of brassinosteroids.
